Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:06.862 --> 00:00:08.320
CHARLIE SAWYER:
I'm Charlie Sawyer.

00:00:08.320 --> 00:00:13.010
I work here in the Cambridge
office on gTech, specifically,

00:00:13.010 --> 00:00:14.800
Google Flight Search.

00:00:14.800 --> 00:00:18.020
And it's my great
pleasure-- have a seat, Ron.

00:00:18.020 --> 00:00:20.310
RON LEVY: I wanted to say
thank you all for coming.

00:00:20.310 --> 00:00:22.940
CHARLIE SAWYER: I
first became acquainted

00:00:22.940 --> 00:00:27.940
with Ron in 1970, when I
was researching a book that

00:00:27.940 --> 00:00:33.940
became a biography of
B.B. King after a 10- year

00:00:33.940 --> 00:00:38.050
search and rejection
by 53 publishers.

00:00:38.050 --> 00:00:40.470
And it was published
by Doubleday.

00:00:40.470 --> 00:00:44.930
Now at that same time, Ron
was working on a book himself.

00:00:44.930 --> 00:00:48.320
I don't know if he
was really fully aware

00:00:48.320 --> 00:00:50.360
that he was working on a book.

00:00:50.360 --> 00:00:52.600
And he was doing
research, we might say.

00:00:52.600 --> 00:00:55.400
And it took another, what, 30?

00:00:55.400 --> 00:00:56.457
40 years of research--

00:00:56.457 --> 00:00:57.665
RON LEVY: But who's counting?

00:00:57.665 --> 00:01:01.810
CHARLIE SAWYER: --to
realize this book,

00:01:01.810 --> 00:01:08.090
which is our topic today,
"Tales of a Road Dog."

00:01:08.090 --> 00:01:12.150
And the way we've
decided to structure

00:01:12.150 --> 00:01:14.830
this is I'm going to
start with the question

00:01:14.830 --> 00:01:17.810
I think everybody
will have in mind.

00:01:17.810 --> 00:01:21.170
Then Ron will give us a tour of
the content of the book, which

00:01:21.170 --> 00:01:24.910
is an ebook, as well as
the book you've seen here.

00:01:24.910 --> 00:01:27.760
So I'll start with
this question, Ron.

00:01:27.760 --> 00:01:32.820
How does a 19-year-old
white kid from Brookline

00:01:32.820 --> 00:01:35.135
become B.B. King's organ player?

00:01:35.135 --> 00:01:36.010
How does that happen?

00:01:36.010 --> 00:01:36.760
RON LEVY: OK.

00:01:36.760 --> 00:01:43.730
Well, first of all-- I'll sit
here-- I was 18, actually.

00:01:43.730 --> 00:01:49.500
And actually my father and B.B.
belonged to the same squash

00:01:49.500 --> 00:01:53.450
club, the Boston
Athletic Association.

00:01:53.450 --> 00:01:56.330
And they used to-- they would
swap partners playing squash.

00:01:56.330 --> 00:01:57.707
CHARLIE SAWYER: You're joking.

00:01:57.707 --> 00:01:58.540
RON LEVY: Yes, I am.

00:01:58.540 --> 00:01:59.623
CHARLIE SAWYER: All right.

00:01:59.623 --> 00:02:01.370
RON LEVY: OK.

00:02:01.370 --> 00:02:03.886
CHARLIE SAWYER: That's
not the B.B. I know.

00:02:03.886 --> 00:02:06.260
RON LEVY: Yeah, I figured you
didn't know that about B.B.

00:02:06.260 --> 00:02:07.020
CHARLIE SAWYER: No, I didn't.

00:02:07.020 --> 00:02:08.880
RON LEVY: He was
excellent at squash.

00:02:08.880 --> 00:02:10.840
He couldn't beat my dad, though.

00:02:10.840 --> 00:02:12.500
B.B. had him over a [INAUDIBLE].

00:02:12.500 --> 00:02:14.289
CHARLIE SAWYER:
What's the real story?

00:02:14.289 --> 00:02:14.830
RON LEVY: OK.

00:02:14.830 --> 00:02:21.970
So before I played with
B.B., I was-- actually,

00:02:21.970 --> 00:02:25.010
I had first met B.B.
When I was about 15.

00:02:25.010 --> 00:02:30.570
And I went to Roxbury
one Saturday night

00:02:30.570 --> 00:02:33.035
to this place called
Louie's Lounge.

00:02:33.035 --> 00:02:38.490
And I was underage, and I
stood out there in the alleyway

00:02:38.490 --> 00:02:41.750
and listened to the
music through the door.

00:02:41.750 --> 00:02:42.250
OK.

00:02:42.250 --> 00:02:45.430
So fast forward a
couple of years.

00:02:45.430 --> 00:02:50.440
The same year, I had a
little band in high school.

00:02:50.440 --> 00:02:55.090
And we ended-- Don Long, the
famous promoter here in Boston

00:02:55.090 --> 00:03:01.110
who does many concerts and
owned The Paradise and what not.

00:03:01.110 --> 00:03:03.350
He was going to
Harvard at the time,

00:03:03.350 --> 00:03:07.960
and he was our manager
of my high school band.

00:03:07.960 --> 00:03:10.190
And if you ask me
the name of the band,

00:03:10.190 --> 00:03:13.850
we changed the name of the band
pretty much every other week.

00:03:13.850 --> 00:03:18.240
So we had 50 different names
over the course of a couple

00:03:18.240 --> 00:03:20.660
years.

00:03:20.660 --> 00:03:23.470
But anyway, he got us
these gigs backing up

00:03:23.470 --> 00:03:27.550
Big Mama Thornton
and John Lee Hooker.

00:03:27.550 --> 00:03:30.370
And we became friends
with Muddy Waters Band

00:03:30.370 --> 00:03:35.180
and Howling Wolf's
band at the Club 47,

00:03:35.180 --> 00:03:39.540
and Luther Johnson, who played
with Muddy-- not the Luther

00:03:39.540 --> 00:03:44.310
Johnson Guitar Junior, but the
Georgia boy Luther Johnson.

00:03:44.310 --> 00:03:47.950
So we started to get into
this whole mix of playing

00:03:47.950 --> 00:03:50.130
with these Bo Diddley
and Chuck Berry.

00:03:50.130 --> 00:03:53.890
Whenever they would come to
town, we would play with them.

00:03:53.890 --> 00:03:57.740
And then Albert King
was playing in Boston

00:03:57.740 --> 00:03:59.550
and on Lennie's on the Pike.

00:03:59.550 --> 00:04:03.900
And Lenny Sokolov, he just
passed away last week.

00:04:03.900 --> 00:04:07.880
Well, anyway, we were opening
up the show for Albert.

00:04:07.880 --> 00:04:10.670
And we finished our set,
and it was very nice crowd,

00:04:10.670 --> 00:04:14.810
and they thought we were
great, for little kids playing.

00:04:14.810 --> 00:04:18.000
And we just heard this ruckus
backstage and all this yelling

00:04:18.000 --> 00:04:24.210
and furniture being moved
through the air against walls.

00:04:24.210 --> 00:04:28.200
And turns out Albert
fired his band on the spot

00:04:28.200 --> 00:04:32.280
and hired us to back him up.

00:04:32.280 --> 00:04:35.300
Now he took my
drummer and myself

00:04:35.300 --> 00:04:36.790
out on the road with him.

00:04:36.790 --> 00:04:40.110
And that's a whole long story
that's funny in the book

00:04:40.110 --> 00:04:42.290
that you'll hear about.

00:04:42.290 --> 00:04:45.740
But after I had been with Albert
for about a year and a half--

00:04:45.740 --> 00:04:48.860
and Albert was reputed to
be one of the hardest people

00:04:48.860 --> 00:04:52.820
to work with-- I mean, it
was-- if you could survive

00:04:52.820 --> 00:04:56.840
the wrath of Albert, you could
survive anything, I mean,

00:04:56.840 --> 00:05:00.760
it was-- it was like
the blues Taliban.

00:05:00.760 --> 00:05:03.291
CHARLIE SAWYER: Is it true that
he had a Thompson submachine

00:05:03.291 --> 00:05:03.790
gun?

00:05:03.790 --> 00:05:05.310
RON LEVY: Yes, he did.

00:05:05.310 --> 00:05:07.830
Many weapons.

00:05:07.830 --> 00:05:10.840
But I only saw him
pull that out one time.

00:05:10.840 --> 00:05:13.730
And he never played with
his guns or showed them off.

00:05:13.730 --> 00:05:15.260
He was very responsibility.

00:05:15.260 --> 00:05:20.960
He was actually a deputy
Sheriff in Lovejoy, Illinois.

00:05:20.960 --> 00:05:23.940
But after playing on
shows with Albert King

00:05:23.940 --> 00:05:29.480
and doing double bills with
B.B. King and Albert King,

00:05:29.480 --> 00:05:32.320
they started to take-- B.B.
King's band, Sonny Freeman,

00:05:32.320 --> 00:05:34.640
the longtime bandleader
and drummer--

00:05:34.640 --> 00:05:38.880
took notice of
Albert's little group.

00:05:38.880 --> 00:05:42.270
And for some reason,
they pointed at me,

00:05:42.270 --> 00:05:47.289
and when the slot opened
up, I got a call from Sonny.

00:05:47.289 --> 00:05:48.830
Actually he called
my mother's house,

00:05:48.830 --> 00:05:53.150
because I didn't have
my own phone then.

00:05:53.150 --> 00:05:56.280
And the rest is in the book.

00:05:56.280 --> 00:05:58.310
CHARLIE SAWYER:
So you were riding

00:05:58.310 --> 00:05:59.772
with the Kings, both of them.

00:05:59.772 --> 00:06:01.580
RON LEVY: Right.

00:06:01.580 --> 00:06:08.310
And my first night with B.B.,
nobody welcomed me to the band.

00:06:08.310 --> 00:06:11.930
There was no set list,
there was no instruction,

00:06:11.930 --> 00:06:15.090
it was just, put
these clothes on,

00:06:15.090 --> 00:06:19.290
get up there play your
butt off, and good luck.

00:06:19.290 --> 00:06:20.930
And that was it.

00:06:20.930 --> 00:06:25.510
Nobody-- we'll get into the
specifics of that a little bit

00:06:25.510 --> 00:06:26.010
later.

00:06:26.010 --> 00:06:27.970
CHARLIE SAWYER: Why don't you
give us a tour of the book now?

00:06:27.970 --> 00:06:28.704
RON LEVY: OK.

00:06:31.370 --> 00:06:41.610
Now this book here
is kind of my own--

00:06:41.610 --> 00:06:46.360
I'd never seen anyone else do
this-- and I came up with this.

00:06:46.360 --> 00:06:50.470
This is my website
here, as you can see.

00:06:50.470 --> 00:06:53.450
I have to look here so
I know what I'm doing.

00:06:53.450 --> 00:06:55.880
I think you can see it there.

00:06:55.880 --> 00:06:59.170
And see where it says,
come for a test drive

00:06:59.170 --> 00:07:04.940
underneath the
picture of the book?

00:07:04.940 --> 00:07:12.625
That takes you to another
page where it's got reviews,

00:07:12.625 --> 00:07:15.580
it's got Table of Contents,
Various Artists, Personalities

00:07:15.580 --> 00:07:19.340
and Subjects, Open Letter
from the Author-- me.

00:07:19.340 --> 00:07:24.010
And then it's got short
excerpts from the book.

00:07:24.010 --> 00:07:26.420
So you kind of go for a
test drive on this, OK?

00:07:26.420 --> 00:07:28.742
So we're going to open it up.

00:07:28.742 --> 00:07:32.030
We're gonna go to
the real book now.

00:07:32.030 --> 00:07:40.880
And as you can see, we've
got a Table of Contents here.

00:07:40.880 --> 00:07:44.820
And wasn't there a question
you wanted to ask me?

00:07:44.820 --> 00:07:46.080
We could go to the book.

00:07:46.080 --> 00:07:50.780
Anyway, what we'll do is we'll
start-- since Charlie's here

00:07:50.780 --> 00:07:55.350
we'll do the B.B. King
Chronicles, Chapter 3.

00:07:55.350 --> 00:08:02.230
So how I designed this
was to have the text

00:08:02.230 --> 00:08:04.890
and then have pictures
right next to it,

00:08:04.890 --> 00:08:07.420
just like a magazine.

00:08:07.420 --> 00:08:11.410
And by being online I
was able to have, like,

00:08:11.410 --> 00:08:14.870
3,000 pictures on
the web book, where

00:08:14.870 --> 00:08:17.930
there's no way I could
have been able to do

00:08:17.930 --> 00:08:21.650
that if it was a print book.

00:08:21.650 --> 00:08:26.140
And then you'll notice,
you'll see it says Meter Maid.

00:08:26.140 --> 00:08:29.910
It's like red highlight there.

00:08:29.910 --> 00:08:34.080
And then you look
a little further.

00:08:34.080 --> 00:08:38.780
And so this has really a
wealth of a lot of pictures.

00:08:38.780 --> 00:08:42.150
Here's a picture of B.B.
King with Sid Seidenberg, who

00:08:42.150 --> 00:08:45.950
was B.B.'s manager,
very-- brought

00:08:45.950 --> 00:08:48.150
blues to the whole world.

00:08:48.150 --> 00:08:50.060
And you'll see a
poster next to it

00:08:50.060 --> 00:08:52.340
that B.B. Headlined
over Jimi Hendrix.

00:08:52.340 --> 00:08:54.500
And it was one of
Hendrix's last shows

00:08:54.500 --> 00:09:00.680
in America, or anywhere
for that matter.

00:09:00.680 --> 00:09:02.300
Sorry, Jimi.

00:09:02.300 --> 00:09:03.759
Here's a picture
of B.B.'s old bus.

00:09:03.759 --> 00:09:05.591
CHARLIE SAWYER: That
picture of Ed Sullivan,

00:09:05.591 --> 00:09:06.480
I took that picture.

00:09:06.480 --> 00:09:08.150
RON LEVY: There
was a picture of--

00:09:08.150 --> 00:09:09.750
CHARLIE SAWYER: There's
one at the High Chaparral,

00:09:09.750 --> 00:09:11.083
but it's farther down, probably.

00:09:13.500 --> 00:09:15.180
But the picture of--

00:09:15.180 --> 00:09:17.900
RON LEVY: The picture
that's in the print book.

00:09:17.900 --> 00:09:21.360
It's like-- so is that good?

00:09:21.360 --> 00:09:25.183
Does anybody have any
questions about this?

00:09:25.183 --> 00:09:27.682
AUDIENCE: How long did it take
you to put the book together?

00:09:27.682 --> 00:09:32.030
RON LEVY: Well, it came
in different stages.

00:09:32.030 --> 00:09:38.050
The production of this on the
web book took about almost

00:09:38.050 --> 00:09:39.180
a year.

00:09:39.180 --> 00:09:42.240
And what I did, too--
I didn't work on it

00:09:42.240 --> 00:09:46.310
for a full year just in a
row, because what I want to do

00:09:46.310 --> 00:09:49.380
is work on-- just dedicate
myself to it like for two

00:09:49.380 --> 00:09:53.690
or three, four months, and
then walk away from it.

00:09:53.690 --> 00:09:57.300
And I didn't even think about
it, I didn't like peek at it.

00:09:57.300 --> 00:09:58.770
I didn't do anything.

00:09:58.770 --> 00:10:00.920
And I wanted to just come
back like maybe a month

00:10:00.920 --> 00:10:05.570
later, six to eight weeks later,
and just look at it fresh.

00:10:05.570 --> 00:10:08.000
Because I wanted everything
to get out of my mind so

00:10:08.000 --> 00:10:11.520
I'd be able to look at it
how someone who had never

00:10:11.520 --> 00:10:14.080
seen it before would look at it.

00:10:14.080 --> 00:10:18.240
And how I got this--how
this came about,

00:10:18.240 --> 00:10:21.680
I did not plan this
from the beginning.

00:10:21.680 --> 00:10:25.610
What happened was, when
I wrote my first draft,

00:10:25.610 --> 00:10:29.340
I sent emails to
various friends of mine

00:10:29.340 --> 00:10:33.150
that were there, at whatever
particular chapter I was in,

00:10:33.150 --> 00:10:38.150
to verify my facts and to
see, maybe I forgot something,

00:10:38.150 --> 00:10:41.010
or, you know, I would
tell them, read this.

00:10:41.010 --> 00:10:41.920
Did I get everything?

00:10:41.920 --> 00:10:44.010
What was so-and-so's name?

00:10:44.010 --> 00:10:45.190
How do you spell this?

00:10:45.190 --> 00:10:47.000
And was that the town?

00:10:47.000 --> 00:10:49.960
I had questions myself.

00:10:49.960 --> 00:10:52.070
And most people were
just flabbergasted

00:10:52.070 --> 00:10:54.330
about how much I remembered.

00:10:54.330 --> 00:10:57.160
They just-- they were
going, oh my god.

00:10:57.160 --> 00:11:00.850
Actually, one of my
drummers said to me,

00:11:00.850 --> 00:11:03.540
he said, you know,
Lev, he goes, I

00:11:03.540 --> 00:11:06.020
read the chapter
about you and me.

00:11:06.020 --> 00:11:09.980
And he says, man, I was
going to take a shower

00:11:09.980 --> 00:11:13.802
and get dressed and go to
work and come pick you up.

00:11:13.802 --> 00:11:18.110
Because I had brought
the flavor of it.

00:11:18.110 --> 00:11:20.990
He goes, man, you put
me back like 10 years.

00:11:20.990 --> 00:11:25.000
I thought it was like today
that you were writing about.

00:11:25.000 --> 00:11:29.160
So it was a lot of fun and a lot
of the exchange on that regard.

00:11:29.160 --> 00:11:33.430
But what happened was, when I
sent the emails to everybody,

00:11:33.430 --> 00:11:36.770
then I started adding
pictures to it.

00:11:36.770 --> 00:11:40.410
Then I started adding
links to YouTube

00:11:40.410 --> 00:11:45.310
and I started making
YouTube links myself.

00:11:45.310 --> 00:11:49.030
And it just kind of
morphed into this web book.

00:11:49.030 --> 00:11:51.980
And that's how it was.

00:11:51.980 --> 00:11:54.650
Another thing that was
particularly unbelievable

00:11:54.650 --> 00:11:57.970
about the production of
it was that every time I

00:11:57.970 --> 00:12:01.940
wrote about somebody
or had their picture,

00:12:01.940 --> 00:12:04.400
even if I hadn't spoken
with that person for 15,

00:12:04.400 --> 00:12:08.560
20, sometimes 30 years,
within two or three days

00:12:08.560 --> 00:12:10.560
afterwards I would hear
from somebody that we

00:12:10.560 --> 00:12:13.140
knew in common, or I
would hear from them.

00:12:13.140 --> 00:12:14.480
It was unbelievable.

00:12:14.480 --> 00:12:19.280
It was like a psychic ESP
thing going on, I mean,

00:12:19.280 --> 00:12:21.130
cross country.

00:12:21.130 --> 00:12:24.350
And very much so of people
that had passed away.

00:12:24.350 --> 00:12:27.550
I could really
feel them with me.

00:12:27.550 --> 00:12:29.770
And I could really
transport myself

00:12:29.770 --> 00:12:33.660
back to whatever time
it was, and actually

00:12:33.660 --> 00:12:39.610
just completely recall exact
conversations that we had.

00:12:39.610 --> 00:12:42.990
It freaked me out, to
be honest with you.

00:12:42.990 --> 00:12:44.790
I couldn't believe it.

00:12:44.790 --> 00:12:48.270
And it just kept on happening
over and over and over again.

00:12:48.270 --> 00:12:52.290
And at one point--
Charlie remembers Cato,

00:12:52.290 --> 00:12:54.830
you gave me a beautiful
picture of him--

00:12:54.830 --> 00:13:01.140
and he and I had this adventure
that was just unbelievable.

00:13:01.140 --> 00:13:05.020
And it took me about two weeks
to write about this adventure.

00:13:05.020 --> 00:13:08.900
And I finally crafted
it and came with it,

00:13:08.900 --> 00:13:11.880
and I started to
read it to my wife,

00:13:11.880 --> 00:13:14.010
and I couldn't get through it.

00:13:14.010 --> 00:13:16.390
I started choking up.

00:13:16.390 --> 00:13:18.660
And I had to stop,
because otherwise I

00:13:18.660 --> 00:13:21.260
would have started crying.

00:13:21.260 --> 00:13:26.250
And she came over to me and
she said, honey, are you OK?

00:13:26.250 --> 00:13:29.960
And I just said, you know, the
last two weeks it's like Cato

00:13:29.960 --> 00:13:31.900
and I were together.

00:13:31.900 --> 00:13:34.320
So much, we were like sitting
next to each other riding

00:13:34.320 --> 00:13:36.230
down the highway.

00:13:36.230 --> 00:13:38.170
And it's done now.

00:13:38.170 --> 00:13:40.050
I'm not going to see him again.

00:13:40.050 --> 00:13:43.560
I'm not gonna share
the experience again.

00:13:43.560 --> 00:13:47.960
Little did I know the 400
times I had to reread my drafts

00:13:47.960 --> 00:13:49.390
and do the editing
and everything,

00:13:49.390 --> 00:13:52.470
that I would
experience it again.

